e values of his profession.  The academic equivalent would be those tenured professors who just keep plodding along for decades, never reflecting if there is any point to what they are doing.</p><p>David Brooks:  If you are reading this, I feel for you.  You&#8217;re better than this!  I&#8217;m being completely sincere here.  You can apply your principles of humility and conservatism to your own writing and your own career.  I&#8217;d urge you to start by running a column apologizing to Sasha Issenberg.  Then you could retract the false numbers that you ran in that column a couple years ago, etc.  Really, everybody makes mistakes.  I find it <a href=\"http://andrewgelman.com/2013/03/18/tibshirani-announces-new-research-result-a-significance-test-for-the-lasso/\">helpful</a> to go back and consider my own mistakes, and I think you can too.  When you&#8217;re locked in a cage, the biggest challenge isn&#8217;t how to find the key, it&#8217;s realizing the cage is there at all.</p><p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://andrewgelman.com/2014/04/12/primarily-motivated-make-money-certainly-dont-want-let-people-know-confused-something-shallow-knowledge-certain-areas-want/\">&#8220;If you are primarily motivated to make money, you . . . certainly don’t want to let people know how confused you are by something, or how shallow your knowledge is in certain areas. You want to project an image of mastery and omniscience.&#8221;</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://andrewgelman.com\">Statistical Modeling, Causal Inference, and Social Science</a>.</p>") (wfw:commentRss nil "http://andrewgelman.com/2014/04/12/primarily-motivated-make-money-certainly-dont-want-let-people-know-confused-something-shallow-knowledge-certain-areas-want/feed/") (slash:comments nil "0"))) ("On deck this week" "<p><strong>Mon</strong>:  Transitioning to Stan</p><p><strong>Tues</strong>:  When you believe in things that you don’t understand</p><p><strong>Wed</strong>:  Looking for 